Explain in detail how a transformer language model performs next token prediction, covering attention, MLPs, and the residual stream. Be specific about dimensions for a 14B parameter model with 5120 hidden size. Also, explain how the model’s parameters are distributed across the layers and components of the model.

Okay, let's try to figure out how a transformer language model predicts the next token. I remember that transformers use attention mechanisms and feed-forward networks, but I'm not exactly sure how all the parts fit together. Let me start by recalling what I know about the transformer architecture.

First, the transformer model is based on self-attention, right? So each layer has an attention mechanism that allows the model to weigh the importance of different tokens in the input sequence. But how does that work with the next token prediction?

The model processes the input as a sequence of tokens. For each position, it uses the attention mechanism to look at all previous tokens (or all tokens depending on whether it's causal or not) and compute some kind of weighted sum. Then, this is passed through a feed-forward network (FFN), which is usually a multi-layer perceptron (MLP). The output of the FFN is then used to predict the next token, maybe through a linear layer followed by a softmax.

